<DocsLayout title="Organizations & Members">
  <h1>Organizations & Members</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-slate-400">Workspaces, team collaboration, and role-based access control.</p>

  <h2>Organizations</h2>
  <p>An <strong>organization</strong> is the top-level workspace in Datanika. All resources — connections, uploads, transformations, pipelines, and schedules — belong to an organization. Data is fully isolated between organizations.</p>

  <h3>Properties</h3>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>name</code></td><td>Display name of the organization (e.g., "Acme Corp")</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>slug</code></td><td>Unique URL-safe identifier (e.g., "acme-corp")</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>default_dbt_schema</code></td><td>Default schema name for dbt projects (default: "datanika")</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Example</h3>
  <p>When you sign up, you create your first organization. You can then invite team members and assign roles.</p>
  <pre><code set:html={`Organization: "My Data Team"
Slug: my-data-team
Default dbt schema: analytics`} /></pre>

  <h2>Members & Invitations</h2>
  <p>Each user can belong to multiple organizations. A <strong>membership</strong> defines the relationship between a user and an organization, including their role.</p>

  <h3>How to invite members</h3>
  <p>You can invite anyone by email — they don't need an existing account.</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
    <li>Go to <strong>Settings</strong> in the sidebar</li>
    <li>In the <strong>Invitations</strong> section, enter the person's email and select a role</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Send Invitation</strong></li>
    <li>The person receives an email with a link to accept the invitation</li>
    <li>If they already have an account, they are added immediately. If not, the link takes them to sign up and auto-joins the organization after registration.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Pending invitations can be cancelled before they are accepted.</p>

  <h3>Managing members</h3>
  <p>To change a member's role, use the role dropdown next to their name in the members table. To remove a member, click the <strong>Remove</strong> button.</p>

  <h2>Roles</h2>
  <p>Datanika uses four roles with hierarchical permissions:</p>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Permissions</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Owner</code></td><td>Full access. Can delete the organization, manage billing, and transfer ownership.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Admin</code></td><td>Manage members, connections, and all resources. Cannot delete the organization.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Editor</code></td><td>Create and modify uploads, transformations, pipelines, and schedules.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Viewer</code></td><td>Read-only access to all resources, runs, and logs.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Authentication</h2>
  <p>Users can sign in with:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Email & password</strong> — standard registration with email verification</li>
    <li><strong>Google OAuth</strong> — sign in with your Google account</li>
    <li><strong>GitHub OAuth</strong> — sign in with your GitHub account</li>
    <li><strong>SSO (SAML / OIDC)</strong> — Enterprise plan only. Configured per organization.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>OAuth and SSO users are automatically created on first sign-in. No separate registration step is needed.</p>

  <h3>Email Verification</h3>
  <p>On the cloud edition, new accounts registered via email must verify their email address before accessing the platform. A verification link is sent automatically after registration. OAuth and SSO users are auto-verified (the provider already confirmed their email).</p>

  <h3>SSO (Enterprise)</h3>
  <p>Organizations on the Enterprise plan can configure SAML or OIDC single sign-on. This allows team members to authenticate via your company's identity provider (Okta, Azure AD, Google Workspace, etc.).</p>
  <p>SSO is configured in <strong>Settings</strong> by an organization owner or admin. Each organization can have one active SSO configuration.</p>

  <h3>Bot Protection</h3>
  <p>Login and signup forms are protected by reCAPTCHA v3 (invisible, score-based) when configured. This prevents brute-force attacks and automated abuse without adding friction for real users.</p>
</DocsLayout>
